primarily responsible for extending and rotating the head. It is part of the transversospinalis group of muscles, which are involved in movements of the vertebral column and head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emultifidus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle plays a key role in stabilising vertebral joints. It is a deep muscle of the back that helps maintain posture and stabilise the spine during movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuboccipital muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are a group of muscles located at the base of the skull. They are involved in stabilising movements of the head, particularly in fine motor control and proprioception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the specific functions of these muscles is important in diagnosing and managing musculoskeletal complaints related to the neck and back.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The semispinalis muscle primarily functions to extend and rotate the head.","The multifidus muscle is crucial for stabilising vertebral joints.","The suboccipital muscles are involved in stabilising movements of the head."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58675"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18018"}},"stemMedia":{"data